x0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCentral to discussions of multiculturalism and minority rights in modern liberal societies is the idea that the particular demands of minority groups contradict the requirements of equality, anonymity, and universality for citizenship and belonging. The contributors to this volume question the significance of this dichotomy between the universal and the particular, arguing that it reflects how the modern state has instituted the basic rights and obligations of its members and that these institutions are undergoing fundamental transformations under the pressure of globalization. They show that the social bonds uniting groups constitute the means of our freedom, rather than obstacles to achieving the universal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCitizenshipxPhilosophy. 0aLiberalismxPhilosophy. 0aUniversals (Philosophy) 0aUniversals (Philosophy). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh1 aDumouchel, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDumouchel, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGotoh, Reiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGotoh, Reiko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHonneth, Axel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKurasawa, Fuyuki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevey, Geoffrey Brahm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagatti, Mauro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahajan, Gurpreet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalaver, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular